  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Possible enhanced sentences for more complex cases\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeitures of assets involved in laundering\n- Fines can reach up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n- Civil penalties and asset seizure\n\nSpecific penalties depend on factors like the amount of money laundered, involvement in other criminal activities, and individual case circumstances. The exact punishment is determined by federal sentencing guidelines and judicial discretion.\n\nNote: This is general legal information, not specific legal advice. For detailed guidance about a specific situation, consulting a qualified legal professional is recommended.",
